{"/service/ndnp/kyu/batch_kyu_iron_ver01/data/sn86069309/00280763652/1921020901/0818.xml":{"full_text":"I\n'Oft\nTMB\nIJUCKINRIDOI NIWI\nCLOVIRPORT, KENTUCKY\n\nFEBRUARY t, mt\ni 'I,1\nI Ml i a, ,i i g\nIP\ni\nu f\nThe? Breckenridge News\nJNO. D. BABBAQB, Editor and PaUhher\nEIQHT PAGES\nISSUED EVERY WEDNESDAY\n1876\n45th YEAR OF SUCCESS\n1921\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nSubscription price $8.00 a yrs $1.00 lor 6 months; 80c for 3 monthi. Buslneji Locals 10c\nwt line and Be (or each additional Imertlon. Card of Thankt, over 0 lines, charged for at\nthe rat' of 10c per line. Obituaries charged for at the rate of Be per line, money in\nadvance. Examine the label on your paper. If la it not correct, please notify us.\nNOTICE TO SUBSCRIBERS\nWhen you have finlihed reading your copy of TUB BRECKENRIDOE NEWS hand It to\na friend who It not a subscriber; do not throw it away or destroy It.\nWEDNESDAY,..\n...FEBRUARY 9, 1921\nPLAYING THE FOOL.\nThat's what, as a nation, we seem inclined to do. We haven't had enough\nwar. We evidently relished the loug lists of dead and wounded that used to\nfill up the columns of the daily press. We want still heavier taxes. Wc\nhave grown fond of wasting money. Wc want to waste a few billion more.\nSo wc have begun to talk about the greatest navy in the world. We in\ntend to be ready for Japan. If the leading nations of the earth, after these\npast six years haven't sense enough to take some effective steps to reduce\narmament and to end war, they deserve to be abandoned by Heaven to\ndestroy themselves.\nThink of the demand of the Secretary of the Navy for 039 millions of\ndollars, and the Secretary of War asking for 099 millions for the year 19211\nFour schoolboys, one an American, one an Englishman, one a Frenchman,\nand one a Japanese, could come to an agreement that would make war an\nimpossibility. But hand the matter over to the diplomat and the case is\ndeclared hopeless. Our Dumb Animals.\nOUR GREATEST NEED\nA new school building is the crying need in our community at present.\nThe population among the children has so increased in the last two years\nthat our public school building is not large enough to accommodate the\npupils. Before next fall, more rooms will have to be added to the present\nbuilding or else a new High School be built.\n$30,000 was raised in private subscriptions by Cloverporters for the Fed\neral Highway. If half that sum could be raised in the same way, wc could\nbuild a High School and an auditorium together that would benefit our\ncommunity bevond the price of dollars and cents. A visit to your public\nschool will convince you of the dire need of such a building. Something j\nlias to be uonc to enlarge tne school wiiy noi duuu a new structure iur\nthe High School with an auditorium in connection with it and in the clown\ntown district?\nSTANDARD OIL CO.\nREDUCES PRICES\nAlso Cuts Wages. Gasoline Re\nduced Cent a Gallon in Sev\neral States.\nIt is interesting to note that out of the 1,'JOO, the total number of suicides\nin the United States last year, there were only three editors, the smallest\nnumber in any class of suicides. Do editors get immuned to all their worries\nand troubles more than others?\nDr. Welch, of Louisville, is getting down to \"rock bottom\" of the evils\ngoing on in his city. Every town needs a Dr. Welch there is work for\none in Clovcrport.\nLincoln, whose birthday is Saturday, is credited with having said \"There\nis not much to man that is not wiser today than yesterday.\"\nHeard the robins yet?\nFARM AND STOCK\nCircuit Court opens at Hardinsburg\nnext Monday. Examine your label.\nMr. Babbage will be there.\nRay Pate living out on the pike\nmade the banner sale of yellow prior\nat the Clovcrport Loose Leaf House\nlast Friday. He had three baskets one\n500 pounds that brought $44 per 100\npounds one 190 pounds at $U9 andone\n293 pounds at $23. This tobacco was\ngrown on less than an acre of ground.\nIt shows what land will do for you\nif you treat it right. Mr Pate did this\nand got results.\nMrs. William Clark was well pleas\ned with a sale she made. She sold\nthree baskets one at $23.23, one at $20\none at $10.23 and one at $:s. Mrs. Clark\nlives in town and does lightfarming.\nShe rented a piece of ground and put\nout a small crop of tobacco and corn,\ndid all the work, was on her job early\nand late and has a little ahead. She\ndeserves to be rewarded.\nA. X. Skillman, Hardinsburg, had\n11 baskets that brought goo'd round\nprices viz one at $33, one $29.30,\none $29. one $2.'1.30, one $19.73, one\n$17 73, one $13.30, one $14.23, one\n$8.23, one $8 and one at $7. Mr. Skill\nman\" average was around $18. His\ntobacco was well assorted as to color\nand length neatly packed on the bas\nkets and in good order. The Amer\nican and Imperial buyers had some\nlively bidding on tlii lot as well as\non all the better grades. They passed\nby the low grades.\no\n1 Low grades went down to the very\ndepths 50 cents per one hun\ndred pounds and up to $2. There was\na lot of these 50 and $1, baskets. Bob\nPierce and Mr. Baldridge were in line\nfor these grades. Hurley's were not in\nthe lime light at all. There were sonic\npretty good looking baskets that\nwould have brought last year $40 to\n$50 had no attention.\nThos Rogers and family have mov\ned back to Clovcrport, from Olaton.\nMi, and Mrs. Ben Anthony have\nmoved to Kirk, their former home.\nMr. J. L. Thompson, Harncd re\nturned from Owcnsboro, Monday. He\nhad been visiting his children in Dav\niess county.\nThe Claycoinb Brothers certainly\nhave a host of friends at their old\nhome. The depot was crowded last\nMonday when they departed for\nCloverport. It looked from the size\nof the crowd that everybody, in the\nneighborhood were on hand to tell\nthem good bye, They will have just as\nmany in Cloverport if they stay long\nenough. They will be treated so nice\nhere that they won't want to leave.\nJust a word about your subscription.\nExamine the label see how you stand.\nIf you arc behind put the money in\nyour pocket if you come to Hardins\nburg next Monday and hunt up Mr.\nBabbage. He'll give you a receipt and\none of the prettiest and best almanacs\nyou ever saw.\nNext Saturday is Lincoln's birthday.\nThe Breckenridge News is celebrating\nit with a full page, beautifully illustra\nted. Read it. v\nJoe Mattingly, living out near Mat-\ntingly, was in town Tuesday. He says\nthe whippoor-wills have been calling\nhim for several mornings which he\nsaid is a sure sign of spring.\nStickers win. Quitters lose.\n--o\nThe tide is turning, get busy, let\nloose of your money. Put it in your\nI bank where it can circulate and help\nI you and your neighbors as well.\nI Farmers have been wonderfully\nblessed with a mild winter. Many dol\nlars worth of feed has been saved,\nstock is looking well and now comes\nthe spring grass which will be another\nbig saving and he can go into his\nspring work with a vim and forget\nabout his troubles.\n24 YEARS AGO\nIn Cloverport\nFeb. 10, 1897\nLittle Josie Berry has measles.\n-(o)-Thos.\nC. Dowell, a former resident\nof this city and who has many friends\nhere died at his home at Walnut\nRidge, Ark., last week,\nto the wife of Alex Ahr, To\nbinsport, a fine girl, Thursday, Feb. 4\nMason an old resident of\nthe Pisgah neighborhood near this\ncity, died last Monday. He was 70\nyears old.\nMrs. Mary Haffey, widow of James\nHafTey died at her home near Kirk,\nWednesday, Feb. .'i.\n-(o)-\nBob McQuady, son of J. E. Mc\nQuady, of Louisville, accidentally\nshot and killed himself last Monday,\nwhile fooling with a gun. He was in\nhis 13th year.\n-o)\nThc tremendous gorge in the Ohio\nwhich has broken above 'here ihas\ndone very little damage at this point.\nA few skiffs have been carried off.\n(o)\nOn Feb 4, the death angel quietly\nentered the home of Ben F. and Laura\nHardin and took their darling Lem\nLeoti, a bright child of seven,\n-(o)-\nMattingly Ben Bates, Jr., who re\ncently married Miss Mina Taul has\naccepted a position with his uncle,\nBen Bates, Sr., on the farm for the\npresent year.\n-(o)-\nFalls of Rough Mr. Robert Burton\nand Miss Crella Matthews were mar\nried at the bride's home, January 27.\nAlton Clemons, a cousin of the groom\ngave an entertainment that night in\ntheir honor.\n-(o)-\nHardinsburg C. W. Moorman was\nhere last week and qualified as assig\nnee of Walter Smart. J. C. Nolte, R.\nL. Newspm and F. Frjiize were named\nto appraise the stock of goods.\nLOUISVILLE STOCK MARKET\nBest hogs: 200 pounds up, $9.50;\n120 to 200 pounds $10.00; 120 pounds\ndown $9 25; roughs $7.75 down.\nPrime heavy steers $7.50 $8.00;\nmedium steers $0.00 $7.00; com\nmon to medium steers $5 $0; fat\nheifers $0 $7; fat cows $5 $0;\nchoice milk cows $05 $75.\nBest veals $11. $11.50; medium\n$5 $8.50; common $3 $5.\nBest sheep $3; bucks $2 down; best\nlambs $7 $10; seconds $4 $5.\nNew York, Feb. 2. Wages, gaso\nline and kerosene have been reduced\nby the Standard Oil Company of New\nJersey.\nThe company announced today that\nemployes at all of its refineries had\naccepted a reduction of half their cost\nof living bonus effective Feb. 15. This\nis equivalent to a 10 per cent wage\nThe company announced a reduc\ntion of one cent a gallon in the price\nof gasoline and kerosene in New Jer\nsey, Maryland,. Virginia, North Caro\nlina and Louisiana.\nThe wholesale price of gasoline in\nNew Jersey and Baltimore was re\nduced from 28 1-2 to 27 1-2 cents and\nkerosene from 18 1-2 to 17 1-2 cents.\nThe Standard Oil Company of New\nYork reduced the price of kerosene\nfrom 19 to 18 cents by tank wagon,\nmotor gasoline from 31 to 30 cents in\nsteel barrels and varnish makers' and\npainters naphtha 30 to 29 cents per\ngallon.\nThe reduction of the bonus of the\nNew Jersey corporation affects about\n12,000 workers. Last August the com\nnnnv mi (I its emnlnvcs made an agree\nment that when Government figures\nshowed the cost of living returned to\nthe basis of December, 1919, the bon\nus would be cut in half. While Gov\nernment figures issued on Dec. 15,\n1920 showed that prices had been re\nduced to the stipulated level, the\ncompany nevertheless continued the\nfull bonus until Fb. 15 of this year.\nFRENCH PEOPLE NOTED\nAS EXCELENT COOKS.\nBtJLL FROG RANCH\ni\ni\ni r\n72fs\n1\nGLASS SAND USED\nIN UNITED STATES\nSand Forms From 60 to 75 Per\nCent of All the Glass Manu\nfactured in This Country.\nFrench Housewife Does Her Market\ning Daily.\nWriting under the caption \"The\nEnglishwoman's Home,\" a writer in\nthe\" London Times discusses in an in\nteresting way certain differences in an\nfamily and social lift in England and\nFrance, and concludes that the French\nhave by far the better of it in the ex\ncellence of their cooking. The writer\nsays:\nThe difference between average\nFrench and average English tables in\nsimilar social classes lies not so much\nin the food or the recipes as in the\npurchase and preparation. The Lon\ndon habit of ordering food without\npersonal selection, though it saves\ntime and troubles does not secure the\nbest results. The French cook, or in\nthe modest households the mistress,\nwill hcsrclf choose tlie food day by\nday in the quantities required for the\nday, and see for herself that all she\nbuys is quite fresh. Coffee is roasted\nand ground daily. There are no sub\nstitutes or ready-made condiments.\nThere is butter or the purest olive or\ngroundnut oil. If there is mayonaisc\nit is made at home by slowly drop\nping the oil into the egg, and there is\nno market for ready prepared soups,\ngelatines, partially prepared sweets, or\ntinned foods. These makeshifts have\ntheir uses in English households, but\nperfection is not to be expected of\nthem. Cooks, like all artists, should\nbe given the best raw materials.\nAnd there are other details little\nlssg informative. Wc learn from this\nwriter that the kitchen in the average\nFrench house is twice the size of the\nEnglish kitchen in a house of the\nsame size and the French cook has\nat his or her disposal more than twice\nthe variety of pots and pans to work\nwith. But more important than any\nthing is, we are told, the cleanliness\nthat dominates French cooking. The\n'French cooks believe that cleanliness\nis the one indispensable adjunct to\ngood cooking, and they keep their\nkitchens, spotlessly clean.\nA writer in a farm magazine in\nthis country deplores the fact that as\nmany American women as men did\nnot go to France during the war, this\nwriter observing: \"What has happen\ned is that hundreds of thousands of\nAmerican boys have come home with\na taste for French cooking and we\nhave so few women in this country\nwho know how to cook that way. It\nmight pay us to send 50,000 girls to\nFrance each year for a course in\ndomestic science. For as a nation we\nshould face the fact that we do not\nknow how to cook. We employ\nFrench cooks in our big hotels and\nresturants, but where' good cooking\nis the most needed, namely, in the\nhomes of the people we are immea\nsurably inferior to the French.\nAnd in America we lack nothing\nbut this knowledge of the culinary art.\nOf the materials that go into good\nfoodwe have an abundance far more\nper individual than have the French.\nBut, although, of course, there are\nglittering exceptions, it is true that,\nas a nation, we should learn.\nWhen Joe Mullhaton Carter walked\ninto Wcisenbcrg's Palace of 5 and 10\ncent cats, and took a scat at one of\nthe vacant tables, no one paid any at\ntention to him, even the Bill Asburry,\n\"No Work Club,\" which was in ses\nsion, took any notice of him, but\nwhen in a Joud voice, that fairly\nshook the building, he balled out to\nOscar, the chief waiter, \"Bring me\none dog well broilcif, six eggs well\ndone, six mince pics and a quart of\nwater,\" the members of the \"No Work\nClub\" at once became interested,\nspecially when knowing Joe's finances\nwere extremely limited, and with the\nprice of eggs at 00c per dozen they\nwere wondering where he had so soon\nget above the average members, who\ncould only splurge now and then in\na five cent hand out.\nSeeing the puzzled look on the faces\nof the members of the club, Joe Mul\nhatton turned in his chair to the mem\nbers of the club and said: \"Gentlemen\nof the bunch, I expect to be in less\nthan two years a millionaire, no more\n'backer' will I grow. I have discovered\neasy money, and it won't be long be\nfore you will see me spending mil\nlions, and have money to throw at the\nbirds. When you gaze your eyes up\ninto the celestial skies and sec a\nI'MIUUUl ausillJ UUdllll Ull IMC KCUIIC\nbreeze, ou can say 'that's million\naire Carter's airship.'\n\"You see here is the dope how I\nam going to make this million of dol\nlars; I am going to start a regular\nBull Frog Ranch. You sec Pa has a\nstrip of ground that won't raise any\nthing. It is covered all the year around\nwith water. Now I know I have got\nthe right dope because I got Ben\nJohnson to ask them fellows, who\nstay in the Agriculture Department,\nhow many eggs a she bull frog lays\nand he wrote and told me that 500\neggs was about the average. So you\nsee I have a one scaon business, as in\nthe fall the frogs hibernate. They go\ndown in the mud and stay all winter,\nlive on bugs all summer, and all I\nhave to do is to spend the monev.\nAny One Can See I have a dear! rinr'li\nI by gum.\"\nI I am going to start with only 25\nieinaie irogs. ine tirst season I will\nCLAIMS NOTICE\nAll persons having claims against\nthe estate of A. J. Bridgewater, de\nceased, will please present same pro\nperly proven, to the undersigned Ad\nministrator. The Bank of Hardinsburg\nTrust Company,\nAdministrator, Estate, A. J.\nBridgewater,\nHardinsburg, Ky.\nA Lady in Chicago Telegraphs for\nRat-Snap.\nRead Mrs. Phillips' wire: \"Youell's\nExterminator Co., Westfield, N. J.\nRush $3.75 worth of RAT-SNAP.\"\nLater ree'd following letter: \"RAT\nSNAP arrived, It rid our home of\nrats in no time. Just moved here from\nPa., where I used RAT-SNAP with\ngreat results.\" Three sizes, 35c, 05c,\n$1.25. Sold and guaranteed by Conrad\nPayne Co., Cloverport, Ky, and\nB. F. Beard Co., Hardinsburg, Ky.\nSelf-Controlled.\nAunt Lucy When young Mr. Hug\ngins kissed you why didn't you\nscream?\nVera Pflippe I was afraid some\none might near me.\nget 12,500 eggs,'or tadpoles, which\nmakes youngi frogs and as 'they prtoduc\ntwice a year, you see the first year I\nwould have 25,000 young frogs. And\nwith frog legs selling at 25c per pair,\nlook what I would get out of 25.000\nvoung frogs at 25 cents apiece!\n$0,250.00, eh!\nGee whihcan Christmas, just\nthink if I kept all my first year's crop\nfor breeders. By-gum I would be a\nmillionaire in less than five yearsl\"\nAt this junction he was interrupted\nby the chairman of the Bill Asberry\nNo-Work-Club, Jim Meadows, who\nsaid: Joe, where in the thunder arc\nyou going to sell these frog legs?\nDod-drot-it, at the rate you are going\nto raise them, you will just have the\nmarket glutted.\n\"There is where you are wrong,\"\nsaid Joe. \"You sec I have got Ernest\nI'opham interested in it he is the man\nwho a few years ago cornered the\nmissclto market, and wc arc going to\nstart a canning factory. Why men,\nby gum anywhere you go in a few\nyears you will find in the stores, tin\ncans bearing a label \"Bull\nFrog Legs, Carter's Landing, U. S. A.'\nWhy the king of Tim buctoo will buy\nthem by car load lots.\nRising from the table he said, Oscar\nwhat is the bill?\" Oscar scratched his\nhead a few minutes. \"Mr. Karter, dc\nbill is 49 cents.\" \"All right Oscar,\"\nsaid Joe, \"Here's 50 cents, you can\nkeep the balance of the change,\" and\nwalked out.\nWhen Joe walked out there was a\nstillness in the Bill Asberry No-Work\nClub, that a pin dropped on the floor\nwould have sounded like a railroad\nspike. Jas. Scaton, scenting a real\nestate boom, was busy trying to wear\nout a pencil on figures. Joe Mullen\nwhispered to John Weiscnberg,\n\"when I was magistrate at Balltown\nonce, I sent, a fellow like him to\nLakeland on just such grounds as we\nhave heard today.\"\nRoscoe Davis sat as if. in a deep\nstudy over the gct-rich-quick scheme.\nWhile Jim Sahlie slowly counted up\nthe figures on his fingers. The only\nsound to mar the stillness was that\nmade by Pike, the cook, who, with a\nnail, was figuring on the back of the\nfrying pan for a slate.\nThe stillness was suddenly broken\nwhen Chairman Meadow's of the Bill\nAsberry No-Work-Club, brought his\ncane down across a chair with a\nwhack. \"Boys, I don't believe a word\nhe said. I bet he don't know a bull\nfrog from a Hzzard, and if he has\ngot 25 frogs buried in the mul to get\na start this spring \"how do we know\nthey are frogs, or lizzards, for I\nwould not believe him on oath. Here\nis what's the matter with Joe. He is\na charter member of the old Bache\nlors Club and they have an age limit,\nand they are about to kick him out,\nso you see he wants to get writ up in\nThe Breckenridge News, thinking\nsome girl will see it, and in order to\nRet some of his millions, come rush-\nTruth is stranger than fiction, and\none of the anomalous bits of truth\ngiven out by the United States Geo\nlogical Survey, Department of the In\nterior, is the fact that a thing so clear\nas glass is composed mainly of sand;\nto be explicit, sand forms from 00 to\n75 per cent of all glass manuafcttired.\nAccording to recent figures, a little\nless than 2,000,000 tons of glass sand\nwas used in the United States in 1919.\nFortunately, the supply of glass sand\nof all grades is abundant.\nGrinding, polishing and blast sands\narc used to make smooth the rough\nplaces on metal, glass, stone, and\nother hard substances. Blast sand is\nclean, tough, sized sand, composed, of\ncither round or angular grains, which\nis driven by compressed -air through\na hose for such purposes as cleaning\nmetal castings and dressing stone. In\ngun shops, locomotive and car shops,'\nand most other places where heavy\nmetal castings are made, the sand\nblast is used to clean off parts of the\nmold that adhere to the castings. The\nsize of sand used differs according to\nthe character of the duty it is to per\nform. Fire or. furnace sand is highly, re\nfractory silica sand for lining furnaces\nand ladies used to contain molten\nmetal, and so has a place in all foun\ndries. About 500,000 tons of this sand\nis used annually in the United States.\ning with arms outstreatched saying:\n\"Joe, I will be your peach, or your\nlolly-pop,\" and such like. Dod-drot-it,\nit's just plain as day. He has got\nmarrying on his brain. No further\nbusiness the Bill Asberry No-Work-Club\nadjourned, so the members could\ngo home to see if their wives had\ngot in all the kindling and coal for\nthe night E. G.\nTHE MINISTER'S WIFE.\nGertrude Louise Small, in N. Y. Sun.\nTo please the parish she must be\nAs active as a busy bee.\nShe must appear at this and that\nAnd always wear a stylish hat.\nHer call she must return always\nThough she receives ten every day.\nAnd in all things the others do\nShe must be interested, too.\nOn suppers she must serve, and bake\nA \"fancy pie\" or frosted cake.\nShe must be organist and choir\nOr else she will be under fire.\nAnd if opinions she express\nShe' \"dictatorial more or less.\"\nA Sunday school class she must teach\nAnd listen to her husband preach.\nWith patients, fortitude, the while.\nShe must be cheerful, sweet and smile.\nNow if she's human and she is\nShe is indeed a child of His I\nWhat Would LINCOLN\nand WASHINGTON Say?\nThis month, in celebrating the birthdays of LINCOLN and\nWASHINGTON, well may we consider what their comment\nmight be today regarding prevailing conditions in America.\nRecalling the sane logic of the immortal LINCOLN, can not\nwe imagine him very emphatically saying, \"The time for talk has\npassed. The time to act has come. Knowing that the fundamen\ntal principles underlying the Nation's business are sound, we must\npractice the good sense which directs each and every member of\nour great national family to quietly, honestly and promptly con\ntribute his full share toward the return to normal conditions.\"\nAnd is it not possible that WASHINGTON might say, \"We\nmust stop lying, not only to each other but to ourselves, under\nstanding that the greatest good for the greatest number depends\nupon honestly meeting our individual responsibilities one to the\nother.\"\nThe officers and directors of this bank are convinced that we\nare pointed toward a slow, but nevertheless sure improvement in\nfinancial, 'industrial and agricultural conditions. The one way to\nhasten the return of prosperity lies in the active co-operation be\ntween all the interests involved and in the honest rendering of the\nservice for which each of us is responsible.\nWe are ready at all times to extend a willing and considerate\nbanking service which we intend shall be helpful to the greatest\npossible degree in promoting the welfare of this community so\nthat the community in turn, may meet its responsibility to the\ncountry at large.\nThe Bank of Hardinsburg Trust Go.\nHARDINSBURG, KENTUCKY\nA\nf ft i\nJfc\nfc.U, A, Jb.il,\nAJ Jt","height":"28012","width":"19532"}}
